# How Does Deforestation Cause Climate Change? — A Comprehensive Analysis

Deforestation, the large-scale removal of forest cover, is a critical environmental issue with profound implications for climate change. Forests play a vital role in regulating the Earth's climate system by sequestering carbon dioxide (CO₂), modulating energy and water fluxes, and maintaining biodiversity. The process of deforestation disrupts these functions, contributing significantly to global warming and climate change. This report provides an in-depth, evidence-based analysis of how deforestation causes climate change, integrating scientific findings, quantitative data, and biophysical mechanisms.

---

## 1. Deforestation as a Major Source of Greenhouse Gas Emissions

### 1.1 Carbon Storage and Release

Forests act as major carbon sinks, absorbing approximately one-fourth of anthropogenic CO₂ emissions annually through photosynthesis and storing carbon in biomass (trees, roots, leaves) and soils ([Science, 2014](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.aac8083)). When forests are cleared or burned, the stored carbon is released back into the atmosphere primarily as CO₂, a potent greenhouse gas. This reversal of carbon sequestration accelerates the greenhouse effect.

- Tropical deforestation alone contributes about **2.6 billion tonnes of CO₂ per year**, accounting for roughly **6.5% of global CO₂ emissions** ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).
- As of 2019, deforestation is responsible for about **11% of global greenhouse gas emissions** ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).
- Averaged over 2015–2017, global loss of tropical forests contributed approximately **4.8 billion tonnes of CO₂ annually**, representing **8–10% of annual human CO₂ emissions** ([Climate Council, 2022](https://www.climatecouncil.org.au/deforestation/)).

### 1.2 Forest Degradation and Peatland Emissions

Beyond outright deforestation, forest degradation—changes that negatively affect forest structure or function without reducing area—also contributes significantly to emissions. Including forest degradation and tropical peatland emissions raises the contribution of forest-related emissions to **up to 15%** of human-caused CO₂ emissions ([LSE Grantham Institute, 2017](https://www.lse.ac.uk/granthaminstitute/explainers/whats-redd-and-will-it-help-tackle-climate-change/)).

Peatland degradation, often associated with deforestation, releases additional greenhouse gases (GHGs), further exacerbating climate change.

