## 6. Human Drivers and the Scale of Deforestation

Deforestation is driven by:

- Logging and timber extraction.
- Agricultural expansion (including livestock ranching).
- Urbanization and mining ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

Annually, approximately **75,700 square kilometers (18.7 million acres)** of forest are lost globally, with tropical forests being the most affected ([Wikipedia, 2020](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deforestation_and_climate_change)).

---

## 7. Conclusion and Opinion

Based on the comprehensive evidence, deforestation is a **major and multifaceted driver of climate change**. It contributes significantly to greenhouse gas emissions, disrupts critical biophysical processes that regulate temperature and precipitation, and initiates feedback loops that exacerbate global warming. The loss of tropical forests, in particular, poses an urgent threat due to their outsized role in carbon storage and climate regulation.

While fossil fuel combustion remains the largest source of anthropogenic CO₂, deforestation ranks as the **second largest source**, responsible for approximately one-tenth to one-sixth of global emissions when including degradation and peatland effects. Moreover, the biophysical impacts of deforestation—such as altered albedo, evapotranspiration, and local temperature variability—amplify its climatic influence beyond carbon emissions alone.

In my assessment, **addressing deforestation must be a central pillar of climate change mitigation strategies**. Protecting existing forests, restoring degraded lands, and implementing sustainable land-use policies are critical to reducing emissions and preserving the climate-regulating functions of forests. Ignoring deforestation risks undermining global efforts to limit warming and threatens ecosystem stability and human livelihoods worldwide.

